Text: Changes in your period are a common side effect of birth control. But it’s usually a good thing! The pill, ring, and patch can get your period on track (no more surprises! 🙏🏽) and can make your period lighter, while others like the hormonal IUD, shot, and implant can stop your period completely. Sounds wild, but it's totally safe. The only birth control that can have a negative effect on your period is the copper IUD. It’s non-hormonal which is good for people who don’t want hormones but, it can make your period heavier.

Text: Ovulation is the part of a woman’s monthly cycle where she releases an egg. This is the time of the month that she’s most likely to get pregnant if she has unprotected sex. Every woman is different so ovulation can happen at different times depending on the person, but for the most part, it happens around two weeks after her period starts.
